                            <comment id="41812" author="cbeams" created="Fri, 26 Dec 2008 06:30:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Check out @SessionAttributes - it&apos;s probably what you&apos;re looking for.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://static.springframework.org/spring/docs/2.5.x/api/org/springframework/web/bind/annotation/SessionAttributes.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://static.springframework.org/spring/docs/2.5.x/api/org/springframework/web/bind/annotation/SessionAttributes.html&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://static.springframework.org/spring/docs/2.5.x/reference/mvc.html#mvc-ann-sessionattrib&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://static.springframework.org/spring/docs/2.5.x/reference/mvc.html#mvc-ann-sessionattrib&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.claymitchell.net/2008/02/11/spring-framework-annotation-sessionattribute-can-be-confusing/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://www.claymitchell.net/2008/02/11/spring-framework-annotation-sessionattribute-can-be-confusing/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I agree with Clay.  Our documentation on its use could be a little better.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="41814" author="scottland" created="Fri, 26 Dec 2008 16:03:45 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;No, I am specifically looking at dealing with permanent session attributes.  I store user and other data in the session to be shared across all controllers.  &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;According to the SessionAttributes docs:&lt;br/&gt;
&quot;For permanent session attributes, e.g. a user authentication object, use the traditional session.setAttribute method instead. Alternatively, consider using the attribute management capabilities of the generic WebRequest interface.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I really think this will be a useful feature.  It will definitely clean up a lot of code I have seen.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="41822" author="scottland" created="Mon, 29 Dec 2008 04:23:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Another approach would be to add a scope parameter to @SessionAttributes, but I prefer @SessionParam as you don&apos;t have to use @ModelAttribute with it.  The simpler the better.  There are countless times we need to be able to share session data between controllers.  I understand that WebFlow addresses that, but that does not mean we should limit the capabilities of traditional MVC.  &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="70143" author="condor" created="Tue, 6 Sep 2011 06:15:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1 - This seems like such a basic need that I am surprised it isn&apos;t included in Spring MVC already.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I would also prefer the annotation be named @SessionAttribute.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And don&apos;t forget there are also ServletRequest and ServletContext attributes - @RequestAttribute and @ServletContextAttribute annotations?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="70181" author="condor" created="Wed, 7 Sep 2011 02:21:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Come to think of it, it would of course be better to have a single annotation (e.g. @RequestAttribute) with a &quot;scope&quot; element (with value request, session, globalSession or singleton).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="123285" author="rstoya05-aop" created="Tue, 26 Jan 2016 17:10:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Resolving this in favor of &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/SPR-13894&quot; title=&quot;Convenient access to session and request attributes in controller methods&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SPR-13894&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SPR-13894&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; which supersedes this ticket.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                    </comments>
